69","1330–1369":"1330–1369","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1358–1401":"1358–1401","1363–1401":"1363–1401","1300–1362":"1300–1362","1305–1333":"1305–1333","1305":"1305","1369":"1369","1358":"1358","1401":"1401","1333":"1333","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1362":"1362","11 November 1358":"11 November 1358","22 July 1369":"22 July 1369","Burton Lazars, Leicestershire, England":"Burton Lazars, Leicestershire, England","Brentingby, Leicestershire, England":"Brentingby, Leicestershire, England","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Sproxton, Leicestershire,England":"Sproxton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Woodford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, such as Woodford in Cheshire, Cornwall, Essex, Northamptonshire, and Wiltshire. In Scotland, the name is derived from Woodford in Saint Boswells (Roxburghshire).","History: Thomas Woodford emigrated from Lincolnshire, England, to NY in 1690."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Woodford Sergeant-at-Law was born in 1330, in Burton Lazars, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir. John de Woodford, was 31 and his mother, Alice Preste, was 25. He had at least 2 sons with Janetta Brabazon. He died on 22 July 1369, in Sproxton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1330–22 July 1369":"1330–22. juuli 1369","1330–1369":"1330–1369","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1358–1401":"1358–1401","1363–1401":"1363–1401","1300–1362":"1300–1362","1305–1333":"1305–1333","1305":"1305","1369":"1369","1358":"1358","1401":"1401","1333":"1333","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1362":"1362","11 November 1358":"11. november 1358","22 July 1369":"22. juuli 1369","Burton Lazars, Leicestershire, England":"Burton Lazars, Leicestershire, England","Brentingby, Leicestershire, England":"Brentingby, Leicestershire, England","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sproxton, Leicestershire,England":"Sproxton, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1330–22 July 1369":"1330–22. heinäkuuta 1369","1330–1369":"1330–1369","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1358–1401":"1358–1401","1363–1401":"1363–1401"